[normal]Written evidence submitted by Mr J Vaughan (ESG 37)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]I read the transcript of your meeting. I work as a financial analyst for an oil company in Aberdeen. My company has significant investments in the 
[normal]Eagleford
[normal] and 
[normal]Bakken
[normal] unconventional plays in the US. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question 5 (how much energy one 
[normal]frack
[normal] pad could produce compared to one large wind turbine) was, I thought, a very good question. The weather isn't great this weekend so I spent some time thinking about it. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As you might guess there
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]are many variables,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]ranges and
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]interpretations to work with. You could pick holes in all the numbers I have used, but to answer the question
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]you have to make some assumptions. I estimate
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]that 
[normal]between 76 and 171 turbines are required for one[bold]&#xa0;[bold]pad.[bold] This is shown at cell D20 and D21 of Sheet 1 attached.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] My calculations compare the energy output from a gas well compared to a turbine over the lifetime of production.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Looking at the spreadsheet boxes:
[normal]1. This calculates the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]energy generated by a wind turbine over its life span - 
[normal]115GWh.[bold] The 
[normal]Enercon
[normal] E70 is a typical turbine deployed
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]where I live in 
[normal]Stonehaven
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. The comparable energy from a shale gas well is 
[normal]1,096GWh[bold] using the 
[normal]mid point
[normal] of 
[normal]prof
[normal] Davies quote of production.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Here we
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]have to convert volumes of gas to energy.
[normal]3. The volumes quoted by 
[normal]prof
[normal] Davies are likely historic. The shale oil/gas industry is evolving rapidly, with constantly
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]increasing efficiency and increase in production. Here I use the estimated future recovery by EQT, a significant player in the Marcellus.
[normal]4.In this box I calculate the number of turbines per well
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]and pad. Prof Davies said in answer to Q4 that 5.9 
[normal]bcf
[normal] was a very small number. To give that context I calculated the number of houses heated for a year using his mid point for a well is 66 thousand. A more realistic number might be 149 thousand. Included is the number of houses lit per turbine.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On sheet 2 of the spreadsheet I cut extracts from various websites that I visited. All the information I used is either from your transcript or websites I looked up.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In question 17 Mr Doughty mentions £70 billion. The 
[normal]Bowland
[normal] shale was also discussed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The British Geological Association give a range for the resources at 
[normal]Bowland
[normal] (the amount in the ground)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]with a stab at
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]mid point
[normal] of 1,329tcf.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A 10% recovery factor is 133tcf. Current wholesale prices at NBP in the UK are ~68pence/therm. That is £7 per
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]mcf
[normal]. That
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]equates to 
[normal]£926bn[bold]. The mix of hydrocarbons
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]from wells varies widely. The Marcellus is mostly gas. The 
[normal]Eagleford
[normal] players are aiming for the liquids window. The 
[normal]Bowlands
[normal] will be a mix of gas, NGLs and crude.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For comparison if the hydrocarbons were all crude, 133tcf equates
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]to 22bn oil at 6,000 conversion. At
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]$100 oil that is worth $2.22 trillion, say 
[normal]£1.5tn.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Finally can I point out that some of the responses to your questions were a bit naff. The reference to 
[normal]Gaslands
[normal] wasn't clever. We
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]know it was a con. A few other observations:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]- Q9, an onshore drilling derrick is
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]usually between 150ft and 200 ft. "tens of metres" is misleading. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]- Q9, "
[normal]eventually"is
[normal] misleading, drilling activities on a well pad take less than a year.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]- Q9, "for 10 years" is not representative of the production life of an onshore well. It is typically much longer than that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]- Q31, answer "significant number of occasions to 
[normal]refracture
[normal] some of the wells" is misleading.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If a well is prolific they
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]might 
[normal]frack
[normal] it again a few times. "Significant number" is not
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]the norm.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]- Q34, subsidy for shale gas is just plain wrong.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The tax breaks
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]mean
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]that, instead of charging tax at ~62% like the rest of the oil industry, it will be more like 30%, as you say in Q35.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]- Q35, wind turbines "virtually do not need a subsidy now" is misleading.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] They actually do receive significant subsidies, every day.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]- Q39, the answer by 
[normal]prof
[normal] Anderson is not very enlightening.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]"I suppose you could 
[normal]untie
[normal] us from the European gas network" is an entirely meaningless comment.
